{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_franklin_ver01/data/sn89066651/0021110949A/1921012001/0980.xml":{"full_text":"s\nv I\n1 1\nif 7\n1 J\nI\nTHE HERALD, HAYTI, MO.\nfk,i\nvT\n:'s'\nJJj&'J\nI The NEW EDISON\n\"Kie Phonograph vQith a Soul\"\nm. i,i?,'\nUj .91 UL\nCWIE7afT X 1 .Wftik B 1 lli9 \"w\nP i C -T.1 Jf fpagMWWlf!BgffafiB\nla7atr1\nSSfeS&?\nWhat Edison did\nduring the War\no\nFVT TIE of n ial announcement is out.\nJl Ask us l'or your copy of \"What\nEdison Did During the War.\" Write\nfor it, if you can't caH.\n'It tells how Edison left his home and\nbusiness and went to sea, how Edison's\n\"Yankee magic\" foiled the German\nsubmarines.\nThe bulletin tells many other things\nEdison did while Chairman of the Naval\nConsulting Board. It explains how\nEdison kept the price of his phonograph\nat bed rock during an era of high costs\nand soaring prices. Since 1914 the New\nEdison has advanced in price Jess than\n15 and part of this is war tax.\nThis bulletin also describes the Bud\nget Plan, which makes it possible for\nevery home to enjoy the benefits of good\nmusic without feeling the financial\noutlay.\np -STe: f l. e: r s ztsza.\nireicjt jar iht nnmnecmeut\nHr. Bdiun'a New Rttearchl\n9 c\nft\nuattawHBwnoraM\nROM THE FARM BUREAU NEWS\nANNUAL REPORT OF COUN-j\nTY AGENT.\nThe work of the County\nAgent for the past year has'\noeen directed in a way so as to J\nget results and I am asking\nevery farmer to read this thru,\nthat he may know what has\nbeen done. It is very difficult\nfor one man to reach each and\nevery farmer in the county and\ndo personal work with him, but\neach man can read this report\nand see that some farmers have\nbeen using the county agent\nand that the work for the coun\nty as a whole has been a suc\ncess. The work began last Decem\nber At that time we had scar\ncely no farmers' organization\nand your county agent did not\nknow a man in the county. It\nwas necessary to know the men\npersonally, where they live and\nwhat they were interested in\ndoirig. This has not been fully\naccomplished for thexe are\nmany farmers that I have not\nmet, do not know their names\n'rfor faces and have no idea\nwhere they live. The fellow\nwho has helped me in getting\n.acquainted is the first that 1\nhave learned.\ntrhe next problem was to get\n.....working organiaztion of the\nfarmers. A membership cam\npf&n was arranged and soli\ncfts procured to do the work.\nThjefcampaign was thoroly or\nganized and the results were\ngooSi We asked the farmers\nto sign a contract that they\nwould pay an annual member\nship ee of. $5.00 for life. 754\nsigned this' contract; not only\nthat but they contributed\n$1004.00 to the State Federa\ntion fund.\nFollowing our membership\ncampaign we had our annual\nmeeting .adopted the constitu\ntion and by-laws, and elected\nofficers. IIore than four hun\ndred tanners attended this\nmeeting.\nThen we called township\nmeetings for the purpose of\nelecting a committeeman or\nrepresentative from each town\nship, to speak for the members\nfrom that section.\nThe executive committee\nmeeting was scheduled for the\nfirst Saturday in each month.\nThese meetings have been well\nattended thruout the entire\nyear; we have never failed to\nhave a quorum.\nThe program of work was\nworked out by the Executive\nCommittee and the County\nAgent. It was decided that\nthe work should be done with\ncotton, corn, hog feeding,\npoultry, and boys' and girls'\nclubs. In addition to this we\nleft time for the County Agent\nto help in emergencies, such as\ninsect control or anything that\nmight arise.\nThe work with cotton has\nbeen along the line of getting\nthe farmers to plant pure seed,\npick it clean and sell in the lint\nThis is more than one years'\nwork but we have been ham\nmering along, getting results\nall of the time.\nThe gin-run seed will bo\nplanted next year but many of\nthe men will change this year\nand more of them next year.\nThe men who have had a pure\nseed of an early maturing va\nriety have been requested to\nsave such seed for planting.\nFor the clean picking we\nhave had the co-operation of\nthe gins in so far as they have\nrefused to either gin or buy\n\"snapped\" cotton. Last year\nwe seldom ever saw a clean\nload of cotton, especially this\nlate in the season, but it is com\ning clean this time. The price\nhas probably had something to\ndo with this.\nWe have done very little to\nget' the farmers to gin and\ngrade their cotton other than\njust advocate it by circular\nletters and in conversation.\nThe work with corn has been\nin selecting pure seed, securing\na market for .some of the fel\nlows and recommending the St.\nCharles variety.\nWe have five co-operators in\nhog feeding, but this has not\nbeen worked very much.\nA poultry specialist has been\nwith us twice during the year,\nhas culled nineteen flocks, in\ncluding 750 birds.\nFor the ladies, especially,\nwe have had a specialist to givi\ndemonsh'ations in canning, all\nover the county; also some\nwork on dietetics has been\ndone.\nThe boys' and girls' club\nwork has been one of the best\npieces of work 'for the year.\nWe have persuaded the banks\nto to put $500.00 into pure\nbred pigs that were given out\nunder the Endless Chain plan.\nThirty-nine pigs have been\ngrown and thirty-two of these\nwere exhibited at the County\ni fair. We have been iollowmg\nthis club work carefully and\nthe boys and girls have been\ngiven a course of training that\nwill be very helpful in not only\nmaking good hogs, but in mak\ning better boys and girls.\nThe Alfalfa Growers 'Asso\nciation was organized 'and in\ncorporated for $3000. They\nhave employed a manager and\nhe has been selling hay. This\nhas probably caused the price\nof hay to be about $5.00 per\nton higher that it would have\nbeen, had all of this hay been\nsold thru the usual channels.\nStill it is not any more expen\nsive for the consumer.\nThe sunflower growers have\nbeen organized in connection\nwith the Southeast Missouri\nSunflower Growers' Associa\ntion, and many of them have\npooled their seed. The seed\nthat have been sold thru the\norganization have brought 5V-\ncents, while those sold outside\nhave brought less than three\ncents. The men who have\npooled their seed have been\nable to borrow about one and\na fourth cents per pound on\ntheir seed.\nThe County Agent has spent\nsome time getting exhibits for\nthe Southeast Missouri District\nFair and the County Fair. The\ncounty fair has never had a\nvery good agricultural display\nand this year the farmers say\nthis was the best ever shown.\nSome outbreaks of army\nworm and red spider have been\nreported and the County Agent\nwas called on for help.\nThere has been lots of mis\ncellaneous work. The Farm\nBureau Officers have been used\nas a soui'ce of information all\nthe time, and we have always\nbeen at the service of the far\nmers who called. The topics\nof discussion have been varied\nin nature and I will not go in\nto details. The fact that 1\nhave assisted in va:c'uating\nhogs, advising about this crop\nor that and in almost innumer\nable other things should con\nvince you that the work has\nkept me on the go all of the\nyear.\nTo further illustrate this\nfact I will give you some fig\nures. Number of farms visited 40S\nNo. of office consultations\nabout farm topics 540\nNo. of days spent in field 243\nNo. of days spent in office. G5\nNo. of meetings held 151\nNo. attending at these meet\nings 5160\nNo. articles written for\npublication 145\nNo .personal letters writ\nten 3950\nNo. circular letters 6321\nNo. questionaires sent out 754\nNo. specialists during the\nyear 23J\nCOTTONITIS\nThe October issue of the\n\"Farm Bureau\" \"contains an\narticle \"Greater Cotton Pro\nduction.\" Who wants great\ner production?' Our trouble is\nwe have grown too much col\nnotton and to increase the crop\neither in acres or in pounds per\nacre, would only be adding to\nour woe.\nThe Cotton Belt now has the\nworst case of \"Cottonitis\" on\nrecord, and in most ways this\ndisease is worse than the \"flu.\"\nIt is a natural disease result\ning from a mistaken desire to\nraise and sell, more cotton than\nthe markets can easily absorb.\nivormialy, in tne U. S. we,\nconsume about 5 million bales)\nper year, but our home people\nhave cut down their wants this!\nyear and it is doubtful that our\nhome spindles will consume as\nmuch as 4 million bales froTi'\nSept. 1st, 1920 to Sept. 1, 1921.\nWe ordinarily produce a\ncrop of about 12 1-2 million\nbales (which is about the size\nof this year's crop) and figure\nto export about 7 1-2 million\nbales, or about 1 1-2 times as\nmuch as we ever need at home.\nFrom the cotton raisers' stand\npoint too much depends \"on\nthe other fellow.\" If anything\nhappens to disturb our home\nconsump'on we feel the effect\nin the price; when anything\nhappens to our export demand\nour cotton gows down to the\npoint of low; when both our\nhome con?umpt!on aiu: our ex\nport demt.nd take a si imp we\ngot a bad case of \"Cottonitis,\"\nand the more vj raise the\ni cr v got aiiu the longer it\ntakes to get over it and it's all\nbecause we persist in raising a\ncrop that can only return a\nfair profit when both o-;r\nhome and our foreign dpmand\nare in a fairly healthy condi\ntion or better.\nThe uses of cotton are few\nit can be worn to our advan\ntage, but that is its prime use\nit cannot be eaten to sustain\nlife, nor burned to keep us\nwarm.\nGenerally, it is a one-purpose\ncrop, hence a surplus of\nsupply is slow to be used up.\nTo reduce our surplus it\nwould seem we might well miss\none crop entirely and then fol\nlow with reduced crops there\nafter. This would solve all\nquestions of price if the crops\ncould be thus controlled.\nBut, our neighbors are\nwatching us, while we are very\nfriendly, we know that friend\nship is shallow, and if they see\nus reduce our acreage they will\nimmediately increase theirs,\nand visa versa.\nIt It has often been said\nthat \"competition is the life of\ntrade\" but we realize, too,\nthat in cotton raising \"too\nmuch competition\" is a death\nto profits, and this fully ex\nplains why we watch our\nneighbors, and why they watch\nus. But, aside from this, we\nare face to face with a matter\nthat is even more serious for,\nwhen we look into the records,\nwe find that'a business depres\nsion results in a natural in\ncrease in the cotton acreage\nthe following year.\nIn 1894, the next year after\nthe panic of 1893, we planted\n10 per cent more acres, than\nhad ever planted before and\nthe Government report for Oc\ntober 1, 1894 shows the crop\nwas in\" excellent condition\nwhich means it was well tend\ned. A fact that should interest\nus is that after 1893 middling\ncotton, delivered in New York,\nWe Sell 'Em\nwmm-wMwiALmnmiummwmmimp\nm\nt UVJ\nr.'.\n2\nWe Fix 'Em\nD. D. GARAGE\nHAYTI, MO.\ndid not rise to a price of 10\ncents a pound, in the lint, for 7\nyears, to-wit: until June, 1920.\nWhy was the crop increased\nso much in 1894? Because then\nas now, we had been hit by a\nbusiness depression and the\nfactory hands flowed back to\nthe farms freely. 'The records\nshow that thru the dull time\nfollowing 1924 the acreage in\ncotton continued to be high.\nWhy? Because the factory'\njobs did not open up again for!\nyears.\nWhen the factory job goes\nout men seek such employment\nas they can find and the farm\nis then their main object for,\nonce there again, they can\nraise something to eat and to\nsell hence, as a matter of\ncourse, they welcome this one\nbig chance. We do not blame\nthem we would too.\nIn its effects, to date, upon\nthe cotton belt our present\nbusiness depression is not un\nlike the panic of 1893, and it\nis fair to assume that history\nwill repeat itself, ie., that the\ncotton acreage will naturally\nincrease materially, due to the\nsupply of labor, and without\nany regard whatever for the\nsurplus now on hand or that\nwe aie due for perhaps five\nyears of stagnated over-production.\nUnless we want to take the\nlowest price for cotton, next\nfall, this country has ever seen\nwe must plan for the smallest\ncrop since the civil war. There\nis amply cotton in the world\nnow to supply the world needs\nfor two years if we do not pro\nduce a lock of it in 1921.\nNo man should plant so\nmuch that he would have to\nhire any help in either the\nmaking or the picking and the\nbanks and the merchants can\nnot back men, in 1921, who\nask help to do more.\nLet's stop arguing for 'great\ner cotton production' per acre\nand spend our efforts in devis\ning ways of growing crops for\nthe next five years which will\nproduce something better than\n\"Cottonitis.\"\net's give some thought and\nconsideration to wheat, corn,\nlive stock, and hay.\nRight now wheat is the best\nbet.\nRight now is a mighty good\ntime to put out some pasture,\nusing Red Clover, Alsike, Tim\nothy, Red Top, Japanese Clov\ner, etc., and not failing to re\nmember that it takes two acres\nat least, to support a 900 lb.\nsteer the year around. Less\nspace will never do. Why?\nBecause he must have a surplus\nfrom June to carry him thru\nthe dry summer, and he must\nhave a surplus from November\nto carry him thru the cold win\nter. With two acres of tame\ngrasses a steer will at least\nGARDNER ADMINISTRATION\nHAS BEEN A GOOD ONE\nHon. P. D. Gardner reMred on\nthe 10th of the present month after\nfour years of earnest and faithful\nwork. Upon retiring he addressed\nto the papers of the state the follow\ning letter expressing due apprecia\ntion to them and to the people he has\nserved.\n\"My Dear Friends:\n\"I can not retire from office with\nout expressing to you- my deep ap\npreciation for the loyal support you\nhave always given this administra\ntion through your splendid papers.\n\"We have worked hard up here for\nfour years during tho time inwhich\nthe whole world has been in the re\nmaking. At times it has seemed\nthat we were unable to meet the\nsuperhuman expectancy, and yet now\nthat my term is drawing to a close,\nI cannot help indulging the hope\nthat the good people of Missouri are\nsatisfied with my work.\n\"With very best of wishes and\nhoping that, if there is at any time\nin the future anything that I can do\nto be of service to you, you will not\nhesitate to call on me, I beg to re\nmain, i\n\"Faithfully your friend,\n(Signed) I\n\"FREDERICK D.GARDNER.\"\nSALESMAN WANTED to solicit\norders for lubricating oils, greases\nand paints. Salary or Commission.\nAddress Lincoln Oil Co., Clevelaud,\nOhio\nMr. and Mrs. Otto Kassel of Cape\nGirardeau, who have been visiting\nfriends in Hayti for the past week,\nreturned home Thursday.\nhold his own 365 daysin the\nyear with very little additional\nfeed and he will make a gain\non 300 days out of the 365 on\ngrass only.\nDon't do anything that is apt\nto result in more \"Cottonitis.\"\nRead about the 3000 new emi\ngrants that are landing in New\nYork every day. 15,000,000\nof them coming, they say, and\nthey won't wear much more\ncotton after they get here than\nthey do in their old homes\nacross the sea. See?\nWhy are they leaving Eu\nrope? eBcause fiurope is\n'broke' as a result of the world\nwar.\nWhy are they coming here?\nBecause the west winds have\ncarried the scent of frying ba\ncon across the ocean. Who,\non earth, does not love the\nsmell of good bacon?\nMost of us figure to raise\nsome corn and hogs and much\ncotton how often do we stop\nto think that on every 3 pounds\nof cotton, we produce 2 pounds\nof seed, which goes on the\nmarket in competition with the\ncorn and hogs we raise?\nDoes the farmer feed his\ncotton seed? No, he just sends\nit on to the market to be sure\nhe has one honest competitor\nhimself.\nDoes cotton seed amount to\nmuch? Look it up and see. It\ndoes.\nContributed.\n4\n1\n7i\n\"i\nM\nF1\nw\nJ'\nr\ni\nt\nf\ni\nT\n.,fe&M UWObl\nV- W\" j\n-Uto. auJu, giiKWi'aB'J-","height":"27432","width":"19180"}}
